Enum (Enumeration) in Java:

An enum is a special data type that defines a set of named, constant values. It is used to
represent fixed sets of options, making code more type-safe and readable by restricting
variables to predefined values.

An enum is like a list of options you can choose from.
For example, if you want to represent the status of a user, you might have only three
valid statuses: ACTIVE, INACTIVE, and BANNED.

Example

public enum Status {
    ACTIVE,
    INACTIVE,
    BANNED
}

Now, any variable of type Status can only be one of these three values.

Status userStatus = Status.ACTIVE;
Why Use Enums?
Type safety: Prevents invalid values (e.g., you can’t set userStatus to "DELETED" unless it’s
defined in the enum).

Readability: Code is easier to understand.
Maintainability: If you need to add or remove options, you do it in one place.

Enums in JPA
When you use enums in JPA entities, you can store them in the database as either their name
(string) or their position (ordinal).

Best practice: Store as string for clarity.

@Enumerated(EnumType.STRING)
private Status status;

